  "prompt": "How much, if at all, will cotton khakis shrink when washed?",
  "response": "Cotton khakis may shrink when washed, especially if they are not pre-shrunk. The extent of shrinkage can depend on several factors, including the quality of the cotton, the fabric weave, and the washing and drying methods used. On average, cotton clothing can shrink between 3% to 5%.\n\nTo minimize shrinkage, follow these tips:\n1. **Wash with Cold Water:** Using cold water helps prevent shrinking and keeps the fabric's integrity intact.\n2. **Gentle Cycle:** Using a gentle cycle can reduce wear and tear on the fabric.\n3. **Air Dry:** Instead of using a dryer, which can cause significant shrinkage due to high heat, air drying is recommended.\n4. **Low Heat Drying:** If you must use a dryer, opt for the lowest heat setting.\n\nPre-shrunk cotton khakis will generally have minimal shrinkage compared to those not pre-shrunk. Always refer to the care label for specific washing instructions to ensure the best care for your garment.",
